<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 94 / Fears on quality of some coffee
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Ministry of Agriculture is preparing to investigate sales of instant
coffee after government scientists found that 15 per cent of instant coffee
samples tested contained material other than ground coffee beans.
The adulterated coffee probably included coffee plant husks, skins, stems or
stalks added before roasting the beans, the ministry said.
It said it would probably launch a fuller investigation.
The brands could not be named, because the number of jars examined was too
small to be representative of any one product, it added, noting there was no
danger to health.
Mr Stephen Locke, policy director at the Consumers' Association, said the
survey 'suggests consumers are being bamboozled and conned. It's a matter of
misleading trading practices.'
</TEXT>
