<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 94 / Future of Sizewell C rests on 3.7p claim
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The UK nuclear review will help determine whether Britain will invest
billions of pounds more in the industry. But the debate will swing on an
argument over only 3.7 pence.
That, says Nuclear Electric, the England and Wales power generator, is about
what it would cost to produce a kilowatt hour, or one unit, of electricity
from the twin reactor power station it wants to build with private-sector
funds at Sizewell on the Suffolk coast.
The company's problem is persuading investors and the government that 3.7p
is achievable. Sizewell C opponents say it is wildly optimistic.
The construction of the 2,600 MW Sizewell C is one of the central issues of
the review.
The nuclear industry hopes a new station, probably Sizewell but possibly
Hinkley Point C in Somerset, would be the first of a series of plants to be
built in the next century. Either would be based on the design of the
Sizewell B station, which Nuclear Electric expects to start operating later
this year.
There is virtually no chance of Nuclear Electric's being able to build new
stations while it remains in the public sector, which is one of the reasons
it wants to be privatised.
It may just be able to build another plant if it can convince the private
sector to contribute towards building Sizewell C. That in turn will depend
on its ability to persuade potential investors that the figure suggested is
achievable.
In its submission the company gives a range of possible figures for likely
unit costs at Sizewell C, but Mr Mike Kirwan, the finance director, said
yesterday that 3.7p was the most likely outcome given the company's
assumptions on the capital costs (Pounds 3.5bn), plant operating efficiency
(85 per cent) and an 11 per cent return on capital demanded by the private
sector.
Even the 3.7p might present potential investors with problems. Only a few
months ago the company was talking about 2.9p. Nuclear Electric said the
change was not a climbdown. The lower figure would apply if the plant were
to be built in the public sector, where an 8 per cent return on capital was
considered the norm.
Another difficulty is that the 3.7p figure is more than 50 per cent above
the 2.4p price of electricity this year in the wholesale electricity trading
pool for England and Wales.
Nuclear Electric says market prices will rise by the time the new station is
built. But it does not dispute that a gap is likely to remain and it is
partly for this reason that 'government commitment and support' will be
needed.
Details of that support have still to be formulated, although Nuclear
Electric stressed yesterday that it may not lead to actual expenditure but
could involve government guarantees or setting aside a proportion of the
market for nuclear power.
Ministers' willingness to make such commitments will depend on their
judgment of Sizewell C's unit costs.
According to the Consortium of Opposing Local Authorities, a pressure group
against nuclear power, an approach likely to be taken by the private sector
investor would result in an estimate of 5.8p. This could rise to 7.4p if the
investor is assumed to be risk averse.
Part of the explanation for the gulf between Nuclear Electric's figure and
those of others is that the history of nuclear power is littered with
examples of cost over-runs.
Nuclear Electric says it has revised only once the Pounds 2bn cost (in 1987
money) of building Sizewell B and that was because the government decided
against building other plants in the series and so economies of scale were
lost.
However, the Central Electricity Generating Board, from which Nuclear
Electric was spawned in 1990, revised Sizewell B costs several times, never
downwards. Doubts about Nuclear Electric's Pounds 3.5bn estimate are raised
because the figure is only about Pounds 700m above the present-day money
cost of building Sizewell B, which is less than half its proposed size.
Similarly, nuclear industry opponents are sceptical of its assertion that
Sizewell C can operate at 85 per cent of its potential capacity.
But perhaps the biggest doubts centre on Nuclear Electric's belief that 11
per cent will be considered an adequate return on capital by the private
sector.
PowerGen, Nuclear Electric's fossil-fired generation company in the private
sector, says it uses a rate of return of at least 10 per cent on its
gas-fired plants. The risk on gas-fired plants is considerably less than
with nuclear because they are cheaper and quicker to build.
Mr Kirwan said yesterday that the government's involvement could lower the
risk for nuclear power. Nonetheless the onus is on Nuclear Electric and Mr
Kirwan to persuade the government to participate. Even then they may
struggle to persuade the private sector to follow the state's lead.
</TEXT>
