<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 94 / Post Office makes record profit: Royal Mail contribution of
Pounds 296m to total Pounds 306m exceeds government target
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Post Office yesterday reported record pre-tax profits for the year to
March 31, but claimed its future was nonetheless in serious jeopardy because
of the government's failure to reach a decision on privatisation.
At Pounds 306m, pre-tax profits were 8 per cent up on the 1992-93 figure of
Pounds 283m.
The Post Office's core Royal Mail delivery business contributed Pounds 296m
 -far ahead of its government target of Pounds 225m.
However, Mr Michael Heron, Post Office chairman, said the 'prolonged waiting
game' over privatisation was causing 'planning blight which leaves us
totally in limbo'.
Mr Bill Cockburn, chief executive, highlighted investment shortfalls and a
'worrying' dip in pillar-box mail as further evidence of the need for a
sell-off.
Although mail volumes reached a peak of 64m items delivered daily, a 2.6 per
cent rise on the previous year, the increase was caused by a surge in
pre-sorted bulk mail. The volume of posted and franked mail fell by 1 per
cent, its first decline for more than a decade.
Although it retains a monopoly over the delivery of addressed mail priced at
less than Pounds 1, the Post Office claims it faces strong competition in
the distribution of pre-sorted bulk mail, particularly within large cities.
Mr Cockburn warned: 'Some of our major customers are being targeted by
foreign post offices.'
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, is expected to publish a
green paper setting out privatisation options early next month.
Post Office Counters, which comprises high-street post offices run by the
Post Office and the village sub-post offices run on a franchise arrangement,
made a pre-tax profit of Pounds 25m, ahead of its government target of
Pounds 15m.
However Parcelforce, the parcel-delivery service, made a loss of Pounds 19m,
Pounds 6m more than the previous year. Mr Cockburn said that at least Pounds
10m of business had gone to competitors, and blamed a shortfall in
investment.
More than 91 per cent of first-class letters were delivered the day after
posting, slightly below the Post Office's target of 92 per cent but far
ahead of its 74.5 per cent record four years ago.
Mr Heron said no stamp price increases were planned.
</TEXT>
