<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 94 / Scots investment at 13-year peak
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Scotland had an outstandingly successful year in securing inward-investment
projects during 1993-94, Locate in Scotland, the inward-investment bureau,
said yesterday.
Its annual report, published yesterday, showed that 95 inward-investment
projects were committed to Scotland, the highest number since 1981. Total
investment of Pounds 587m was planned, which would create 7,688 jobs and
safeguard a further 3,384 jobs.
This compares with investment of Pounds 352m secured in 1992-93, which
involved 65 projects and created or safeguarded more than 8,000 jobs.
Mr Allan Stewart, Scottish Office industry minister, warmly welcomed the
figures, but the Scottish Office said: 'Not all projects proceed exactly as
planned. On average around two-thirds of planned direct jobs are achieved.'
Last year's performance will help rebut sceptics who have argued that
Scotland is declining as a magnet for inward investment in face of
competition from the Irish republic, Spain and eastern Europe.
Some 62 per cent of the total planned investment for 1993-94 comes from the
US, and of that, 85 per cent was reinvestment in existing plants, such as a
Pounds 7m expansion by the computer manufacturer Compaq, creating a further
250 jobs.
Some 22 per cent of new investment came from continental Europe and
Scandinavia, 11 per cent from the rest of the UK and 4 per cent from Japan
and Asia.
Almost half of all new investment was in the electronics sector, followed by
chemicals and engineering.
Locate in Scotland: Review 1993-94. Scottish Office Industry Department, New
St Andrew's House, Edinburgh, EH1 3TG. Free.
