<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 94 / Insolvency firms attack 'aggressive' watchdog
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Leading insolvency practitioners have been putting pressure on their
regulatory body to dilute the tough approach planned for inspections of
their firms.
Board members of the Joint Insolvency Monitoring Unit, the self-regulating
body which begins full operation next Monday, debated possible changes to
its approach at a meeting earlier this month.
They discussed concerns over the tone and nature of the information sought
by the unit's inspectors, which they believed to be excessively aggressive.
Their demands included requirements in 'pre-visit questionnaires' issued to
firms before inspection that they list any failures to comply with
regulations - which some firms believed could be self-incriminatory and
could breach concerns over confidentiality.
Mr Malcolm London, president of the Insolvency Practitioners' Association
and a partner with Coopers &amp; Lybrand, said yesterday: 'This was not the sort
of monitoring we were anticipating.'
'We are more concerned with assisting our members to get themselves properly
organised to comply with the rules,' he said. 'Our main concern is not to
discipline them.'
Ms Kay Linnell, chief executive of the unit, said: 'We are not modifying
anything. There is no point in us going in firms with a blindfold on.
'This is an overreaction by quite senior people in the profession. We are
human beings and will use a light touch. Practitioners have got to realise
they are getting a free independent peer review.'
She said firms' internal control systems ought to be able to pick up
compliance breaches. She added that a number of larger firms had 'so many
layers of management' that they were unable to provide comprehensive
information even on their current workload.
She said she had prevented the firms trying to influence which consultants
temporarily hired from their competitors would be allowed to conduct
inspections.
Mr London said of Ms Linnell: 'She is quite single-minded and strong-minded
and not easily persuaded to change her mind.'
The Joint Insolvency Monitoring Unit was set up under pressure from the
Insolvency Service at the Department of Trade and Industry, because the
Insolvency Service did not believe there was adequate supervision of members
of the insolvency prof-ession.
It submits reports to the licensing bodies of the Institute of Chartered
Accountants in England and Wales, its counterpart in Scotland and the
Insolvency Practitioners Association. It is these bodies that determine any
disciplinary action of the practitioners they represent.
</TEXT>
