<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 94 / Upturn 'far short of rip-roaring boom'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bank and building society lending bounced back in May from April's low
levels, according to Bank of England figures yesterday.
But taken with subdued growth of broad money, the latest seasonally adjusted
lending data continued to point to a steady and unspectacular economic
recovery.
Ms Ruth Lea, chief UK economist of Lehman Brothers, the US investment bank,
said the May money and lending figures were 'a salutary reminder that the UK
is not experiencing a rip-roaring boom'.
The Bank's figures, the first to incorporate a new monthly system of
seasonal adjustment, showed bank and building society lending to the private
sector rose by a provisional adjusted Pounds 1.5bn in May.
This was below the City's consensus expectation of Pounds 1.9bn growth in
such so-called 'M4 lending' but higher than April's Pounds 735m increase,
which was revised upwards because of the new method of seasonal adjustment
from an earlier announced Pounds 470m.
Figures from the British Bankers' Association also pointed to unspectacular
lending growth. Its seasonally adjusted data, which is broadly consistent
with Bank figures, showed the nine leading UK banks increased lending by
Pounds 928m in May. This more than reversed a fall of Pounds 501m in April
but was still below the average rise of Pounds 1.08bn in the previous six
months.
Lord Inchyra, the association's director-general, said: 'Demand for bank
lending from the corporate sector remains elusive.' Consumer credit from the
banks remained weak but their mortgage lending increased by Pounds 610m last
month, a rise of 9 per cent on April.
Meanwhile, the Bank reported that M4, its broad measure of money supply that
includes bank and building society deposits and cash in circulation,
increased by a seasonally adjusted 5.3 per cent in the year to May, down
from revised year-on-year growth of 5.5 per cent in April. The May figure
was below City expectations of a 5.8 per cent rise and well within the lower
half of the government's 'monitoring range' of 3 per cent to 9 per cent
annual growth for M4.
The new system of seasonal adjustment also prompted the Bank to revise down
its earlier estimates for growth of M0, comprising mainly notes and coins in
circulation, to 6.9 per cent in the year to end-May against 7.1 per cent
previously.
</TEXT>
