<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 94 / Strike ballot at National Grid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Unions representing 4,500 workers at National Grid, which runs the
electricity transmission system, have rejected a 'final' pay offer and will
hold a ballot on industrial action, David Goodhart writes.
The company offered a general pay rise of 2.6 per cent - the rate of
inflation - as well as lump sums varying from Pounds 200 to Pounds 700. Last
year National Grid gave a rise of 3.9 per cent, well above the inflation
rate, but that included a move towards single-table bargaining and a new pay
system.
Mr Danny Carrigan, national officer of the AEEU craft union, said: 'This
offer is unacceptable in view of the huge increases in productivity and
profitability since privatisation. The company has also recently announced a
15 per cent increase in dividends and a rise in pre-tax profits of Pounds
150m.'
The other unions involved include the EMA management union, the GMB and TGWU
general unions, and Unison, the public-services union.
</TEXT>
