<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 94 / Lawson sceptical of solution to boom-bust
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Pledges by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr Eddie George, the Bank
of England governor, to avoid a repeat of the boom-bust scenarios of the
past are 'somewhat premature', Lord Lawson, the former chancellor, said
yesterday.
'As experience throughout the world makes clear, abolition of the economic
cycle is simply not within the power of any government to deliver,' Lord
Lawson said in a lecture organised by the Social Market Foundation and the
London School of Economics.
Instead of focusing on the short-term vagaries of the business cycle, about
which policy-makers could do very little, they should concentrate on
boosting long-term performance by improving the supply side of the economy,
said Lord Lawson, Britain's longest serving post-war chancellor until his
resignation in 1989.
'The plain fact is that the economic cycle is endemic - which means,
incidentally, that all the current talk of no return to 'boom and bust is
somewhat premature to say the least'.
Lord Lawson, delivering his verdict on the government's economic record 10
years after his keynote Mais speech, which became the blueprint for the
Thatcher years, repeated his criticism of the government's reluctance to
grant independence to the Bank.
</TEXT>
