<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 94 / Retail planning test case to open
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A test-case public inquiry likely to affect out-of-town shopping centres
begins today.
The Church Commissioners, who own the MetroCentre, Europe's largest
out-of-town retail and leisure development, have disagreed with Gateshead
borough council over whether the complex, with 350 retail units, should be
treated as one unit or 350 for planning purposes.
The local authority argues that any change of use of individual units in the
centre and any change of shop front require its permission.
The Church Commissioners maintain that the MetroCentre is one building and
that internal changes should not need consent.
Local authorities are not consistent on planning policy. Some follow
Gateshead's line while some require planning applications only for change of
use, and some do not require any applications for internal changes.
The MetroCentre disagreement has arisen since its Enterprise Zone status,
which conferred a simplified planning regime, ended in 1991.
Mr Chris Moore, for the Church Commissioners' managing agent, said: 'What we
are trying to do is clarify the planning legislation.'
The commissioners said the issue is one of principle: 'It is
administratively inconvenient for us and for the tenants. We also want to
reaffirm our ability to control the centre.'
But Mr Jerry Barford, Gateshead's director of planning, said the council
wished only to exercise its statutory responsibilities. The commissioners,
he said, seemed puzzled that the council sought to exercise planning
control.
Mr Peter Gates, chairman of the centre's tenants' association, said
retailers were concerned at any measures which might increase costs.
</TEXT>
