<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 94 / Rules on lottery spending eased
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sports, arts and heritage groups will be able to apply for revenue grants to
help run capital projects funded by the proceeds of the National Lottery, Mr
Peter Brooke, the National Heritage secretary, said yesterday, Raymond
Snoddy writes.
The announcement marks a new flexibility on how the money raised by the
National Lottery can be spent.
Critics were worried that hundreds of millions of pounds might be spent on
new capital projects but that the money would not be available to run the
new projects successfully.
Mr Brooke made clear yesterday that while the proceeds, which could be
Pounds 9bn over seven years, will be mainly for capital projects it will be
possible to apply for revenue grants.
He said: 'After consultation with the distributing bodies, I have agreed to
allow them greater flexibility in the awarding of endowments and revenue
grants to help cover, in some instances, the revenue costs of lottery-funded
capital projects.'
The distribution bodies which will allocate the money raised by Camelot, the
consortium chosen to operate the lottery, are the Arts Council, Sports
Council, the National Heritage Memorial Fund, the Millennium Commission and
the National Lottery Charities Board.
</TEXT>
