<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 94 / MoD and Treasury battle on cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and BRUCE CLARK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A tussle was under way yesterday between the Ministry of Defence and the
Treasury over forthcoming cuts in military spending, as unrest mounted on
both sides of the Commons.
The MoD is understood to have completed its Front Line First proposals,
designed to shave at least Pounds 750m a year from the defence budget,
mainly by trimming expenditure on support services. Mr Malcolm Rifkind,
defence secretary, said in April he was seeking savings from support
spending, and might use the spare funds to beef up the forces' frontline
capability.
However, the Treasury is now understood to be challenging this. Mr Rifkind
is expected to confirm several procurement decisions around the time of the
announcement of the decision - expected in mid-July - to soften the
political impact of the spending cuts and up to 25,000 job losses.
At Westminster, Mr Julian Brazier, chairman of the Tory backbench defence
committee, was one of a number of Conservatives who attacked plans to cut
support services.
He said: 'I understand there are likely to be cuts in the medical capability
of the forces, which we would need if we ever went to war, and they are also
talking about further cuts in spares and ammunition, which we found we
didn't have enough of in the Gulf.'
At the same time, Labour stepped up its campaign to preserve the Rosyth
naval base in Fife, amid fears that it will be closed with the loss of more
than 4,000 jobs. Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor - whose constituency
contains the naval base - urged Mr Rifkind to make a statement on Rosyth's
future before publication of the report next month.
</TEXT>
