<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 94 / Davenport Brewery building saved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Birmingham City Council has halted plans to knock down the offices of the
old Davenport Brewery, Paul Cheeseright writes.
The offices incorporate a Georgian house which provided the design for other
offices built between the world wars. Limewood Developments, the property
arm of the Greenalls leisure group which owns Davenport, wanted to demolish
the offices while it cleared the site (above) for a retail and housing
development. The planning application for the shops and homes has been
withdrawn. The council wants the office buildings retained but is anxious to
bring life back to a site that is just off the city centre and next to the
old accident hospital, which is to be converted into student accommodation.
