<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 94 / SEC chief 'troubled' by loss on derivatives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Arthur Levitt, chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, said
yesterday that he was 'troubled' by a growing number of reports of
derivatives-related losses at US mutual funds.
In letters to the chief executives of large mutual funds and to the
Investment Company Institute, Mr Levitt said SEC inspection staff had found
reasons 'to raise questions' about the derivatives activities of some mutual
funds.
'It is apparent that at some funds derivatives risks may not have been well
managed, and that resulting losses may have been unexpected by fund
management and fund shareholders,' said Mr Levitt in a letter to Mr Matthew
Fink, the ICI president.
The SEC chairman's expression of concern comes in the wake of reports of
large declines in the value of some mutual funds because of their use of
derivatives instruments.
Mr Levitt is particularly worried about the derivatives activities of money
market and government bond funds because the conservative-minded investors
who choose those funds might not be fully informed of their exposure to the
instruments.
In his letter to the ICI, Mr Levitt said he wanted to know what mutual fund
managers had done to address the risks involved in their use of derivatives.
He also asked several questions about the industry's derivatives activities,
including whether funds were setting and following limits on the use of
derivatives and whether all managers were sufficiently expert in derivatives
to use the instruments properly.
</TEXT>
