<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 94 / 25 die in Iranian prayer hall blast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS, Middle East Editor and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TEHRAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Iran said that 25 people were killed and 70 wounded yesterday when a bomb
exploded in a crowded prayer hall in the north eastern Iranian town of
Mashhad.
The Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) said the worshippers had congregated
at the mausoleum of Imam Reza to observe the Islamic mourning day of Ashura.
The authorities in Tehran immediately blamed the Mujahadeen-e-Khalq, the
main Iranian opposition group, which in the past few years has been more
visible outside the country than within.
However, a statement issued from the Mujahadeen office in Paris 'strongly
condemned' the bombing. It added: 'Such criminal actions, which inflict
casualties on innocent people, only serve the interests of the mullahs'
regime.'
IRNA reported that several people had been arrested. An interior ministry
official quoted by the agency said several of the injured were critically
ill. Earlier the death toll had been put at 70.
Mashhad was the centre of rioting two years ago when official buildings,
banks and shops were attacked and several people killed in protests believed
to have been sparked by demolition of slum housing.
There have been reports of minor incidents in Tehran this year, but none
causing serious loss of life or damage to buildings.
But with last year's fall in oil prices, the government has fallen further
behind in meeting international debt obligations and, with inflation rising
sharply, senior Iranian officials have been aware of the risks of public
discontent. Parliament has refused to sanction price increases sought by the
government and President Rafsanjani's efforts to maintain other economic
reforms, such as a single exchange rate, have been abandoned.
An earthquake measuring 6.1 on the Richter scale struck southern Iran
yesterday killing two people, injuring over 100 and destroying or damaging
51 villages, official media said, Reuter reports from Tehran.
</TEXT>
