<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUN 94 / Lawson scorns plan to beat boom-bust cycle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lord Lawson yesterday derided the government's plans to end the UK economic
cycle of boom and bust, arguing that economies always move in cycles
irrespective of attempts to abolish them.
In a thinly veiled rebuke of Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, Lord Lawson
said: 'The plain fact is that the economic cycle is endemic - which means
that all the talk of no return to boom and bust is somewhat premature, to
say the least.'
Mr Clarke recently pledged that the government would not steer Britain's
economic recovery into a new boom and bust cycle.
However, Lord Lawson, in a lecture organised by the Social Market Foundation
and the London School of Economics, said: 'I have no sympathy whatever for
the more ambitious notion that the objective of macroeconomic policy should
be to iron out the business cycle.' Lord Lawson, Britain's longest-serving
postwar chancellor, until his resignation in 1989, said all attempts by
governments to steer economies 'along an impossibly straight line' by
macroeconomic policy had failed.
His comments angered the Treasury, but it declined to comment publicly.
However, in private senior officials suggested Lord Lawson was wrong to
argue that 'the government could not and would not end the boom-and-bust
cycle that had bedevilled past governments'.
Lord Lawson went on to say that recent events demonstrated the power of
financial markets to impose their will on national governments suspected of
financial imprudence.
Instead of focusing on the short-term vagaries of the business cycle, about
which policymakers could do very little, he urged the government to
concentrate on boosting long-term performance by improving the supply side
of the economy.
He suggested a significant extension of the UK family credit system to
provide top-up payments to all those in work on very low pay, fitting in
with a system of workfare  - making the payment of benefit conditional on
community work.
Lord Lawson also repeated his criticism of the government's determination
not to grant independence to the Bank of England.
'The half-way house alighted upon by the present government, of publishing
the minutes of the regular monetary meetings between the chancellor and the
governor, is an interesting innovation,' he said.
But when it came to raising interest rates, if the minutes represented an
honest account, they could have a detrimental effect on the credibility of
the authorities' decisions in the financial markets. That, he argued, would
outweigh any advantage derived from the new arrangement.
</TEXT>
<XX>
