<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUN 94 / Economic Diary: Other economic news
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Monday: Recent monthly figures for UK bank and building society (M4) lending
have moved erratically, so it is no surprise that analysts' forecasts for
seasonally adjusted M4 lending in May range from Pounds 600m to Pounds 4bn.
The consensus forecast of Pounds 1.9bn compares with actual lending of
Pounds 500m in April.
Tuesday: US trade in goods and services is expected to notch up another
significant deficit in April, with analysts' forecasts ranging from Dollars
7bn to Dollars 9.5bn. However, the consensus forecast, at Dollars 7.5bn,
indicates no change from the March outturn.
Friday: Final first-quarter UK GDP and current account balance of payments
figures will be last economic in-
formation published before release of the government's revised forecast for
the economy on June 28.
First-quarter GDP is expected to grow year-on-year at 2.6 per cent, above
the 2.5 per cent growth forecast for 1994 by the Treasury last November.
The consensus forecast for the current account points to a first-quarter
deficit of Pounds 2.2bn, an improvement on the Pounds 2.6bn seasonally
adjusted deficit of the 1993 fourth quarter.
