<DATE>940620
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUN 94 / International Company News: Japanese bank merger off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A Japanese regional bank has pulled out of a finance ministry-inspired
merger with two competitors, a setback to government attempts to reorganise
the weakest local financial institutions.
Mr Yukio Shimodate, managing director of Kita-Nippon Bank, in Morioka,
northern Japan, announced over the weekend his decision to withdraw from a
proposed merger with bad debt-laden Tokuyo City Bank and Shokusan Bank. The
merger would have threatened the survival of Kita-Nippon, he maintained.
The plan, proposed in April by Kita-Nippon with MoF backing, ran into
intense opposition from customers and businesses, on the grounds that
Tokuyo's bad debts would weaken the other partners.
A Kita-Nippon consumer group had collected 20,000 signatures opposing the
scheme, in an almost unheard of confrontation with government policy. Unions
were also anxious that the costs of writing down some of Tokuyo City's
estimated Y100bn bad debts would hit bonuses and add to the risk of branch
closures.
This was to have been the largest of a series of regional bank mergers
orchestrated by the MoF in an attempt to encourage them to share costs in
the face of growing competition in local banking from Tokyo-based city
banks.
Most regional banks have a solid client base of local business borrowers,
but some second tier banks have built up problem loans from over-lending in
the late 1980s. The three in the aborted merger are second tier banks.
</TEXT>
