<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
When keen to annoy the boys, Maisie of 'The Perishers' used to ask
disingenuously 'Is this the kick ball season or the hit ball season?'
Perhaps she still does, but who reads the Daily Mirror these days? It seems
unlikely, anyway, because the internationalisation of sport has ensured that
there are virtually no seasons any more. Today television brings us the
opening day's play from the hit ball matches at Wimbledon with highlights in
Today At Wimbledon on BBC1 at 10.10. That is followed by highlights from the
last day's play in the England/New Zealand hit ball match at Lord's in
Cricket: Second Test (BBC1 11.10). But the big sports event, of course, is
the kick ball tournament in the USA. Brazil play Russia in World Cup
Grandstand on BBC2 at 8.30, then Holland play Saudi Arabia in World Cup 94
on ITV at 11.40. Those siding with Maisie may prefer to listen to I
Fiamminghi on Radio 3 in a concert which includes work by Handel, Boccherini
and Purcell (7.30) or 'The Monday Play' on Radio 4: The Devil's Province
(7.45). This is about getting by with the locals in Provence ..in 1213 when
efforts were under way to suppress the Cathar heresy.
</TEXT>
