FT  20 JUN 94 / Lib dem spokesman advises union to sever ties with Labour
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
If the trade union movement is serious about adopting Continental-style
social partnership it will have to stop being politically tied to the Labour
party, Mr Alex Carlile, the Liberal Democrat employment spokesman, told a
conference organised by The Guardian newspaper and the Fabian Society.
Mr Carlile said: 'The unions will never become full partners in industry if
they are tied to one party.' He is in favour of unions sponsoring MPs from
other parties, including the Liberal Democrats. He also suggested unions
should help small companies by providing venture capital. 'They would get a
better return than they have got from investing in the Labour party,' he
said.
Mr Clive Brooke, general secretary of the IRSF civil service union, told the
conference that 99 per cent of his union's members had agreed to having
their union dues deducted from pay by their employer, as required by the
government's new legislation on 'check-off'.
