FT  20 JUN 94 / Russian foreign minister denies existence of Korean nuclear
bomb
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Andrei Kozyrev, the Russian foreign minister, claimed at the weekend that
North Korea did not yet have a nuclear bomb and quoted 'experts' as saying
it would take the former Soviet ally three to seven years to develop one,
Leyla Boulton reports from Moscow.
Mr Kozyrev seemed to hint his information came from Russian intelligence
when he cited 'all the sources of information reaching Moscow and not just
the Foreign Ministry'.
While reiterating criticism of the US for failing to consult Moscow on its
proposals for phased sanctions of increasing severity against Pyongyang, he
said there was no point in rushing ahead with them because China would veto
them in the Security Coun cil.
However he warned that sanctions against the hardline Communist state were
'inevitable' if it persisted in keeping the International Atomic Energy
Agency in the dark about its nuclear programme. He also criticised what he
called the Russian parliament's 'North Korean lobby'.
