<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUN 94 / Stand-off in search for EU chief: Kohl opposes Dutch PM as
replacement for Delors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A stand-off between Germany and the Netherlands is holding up efforts to
break the deadlock over the succession to Mr Jacques Delors as president of
the European Commission ahead of this week's EU summit in Corfu.
Chancellor Helmut Kohl remains opposed to Mr Ruud Lubbers, Dutch prime
minister, and is canvassing support for Mr Jean-Luc Dehaene, the Belgian
prime minister, who formally announced his candidacy last Friday.
The implicit threat of a German veto at the Corfu summit has irritated the
Dutch government. Mr Lubbers has sought to call Mr Kohl's bluff by offering
to pull out of the race, but only if the German chancellor took public
responsibility for blocking his candidacy, according to senior diplomats in
Brussels.
Efforts to reach a compromise could turn on a meeting of Christian Democrat
leaders on Wednesday in Brussels, two days before the opening of the Corfu
summit. Mr Kohl, Mr Lubbers and Mr Dehaene are all due to attend.
Belgian officials believe Mr Dehaene can count on as many as eight EU member
states to support his candidacy. Italy, the Netherlands, Portugal, and the
UK remaining are said to be opposed or uncommitted.
The choice of the Commission president is traditionally settled in secret by
unanimity among the 12 heads of government. A stalemate boosts the chances
of victory by a compromise candidate, either Sir Leon Brittan, chief EU
trade negotiator, or Mr Peter Sutherland, outgoing head of the Gatt world
trade organisation.
Greece, which holds the rotating EU presidency, fears that controversy over
the Delors succession could poison the summit atmosphere and overshadow the
visit of President Boris Yeltsin of Russia. Mr Yeltsin arrives in Corfu on
Thursday to sign a new trade and political agreement with the Union.
Senior diplomats in Brussels said a compromise could be reached in the form
of a 'package deal' covering top posts at the Western European Union, the
EU's defence arm, the European Council secretariat, as well as the North
Atlantic Treaty Organisation and the Organisation of Economic Co-operation
and Development.
But Greece's authority has suffered as a result of its unilateral trade
embargo against neighbouring Macedonia and partly because Mr Andreas
Papandreou, the ailing 75-year-old prime minister, is too weak to make the
customary pre-summit tour of EU capitals.
The result is that Mr Kohl has emerged as the principal EU powerbroker, his
status enhanced by his Christian Democrat party's strong performance in last
week's European parliamentary elections.
One favoured scenario would give Germany the post of secretary general of
the European Council secretariat and Spain the top job at the WEU. EU
leaders would also agree to back Mr Renato Ruggiero of Italy and Lord Lawson
of the UK as European candidates for the World Trade Organisation and the
OECD.
Mr Kohl is also said to be willing to consider supporting Mr Lubbers as
successor to the ailing Mr Manfred Worner at Nato.
Topics at the Corfu summit will include a progress report on implementing
the European Commission's White Paper on growth and unemployment; approval
of 11 new rail and road projects known as trans-European networks, subject
to further study and without a commitment for new financing instruments; and
the signing of the EU accession treaties by the leaders of Austria, Finland,
Sweden and Norway.
Greece is also expected to make a pitch for the opening of accession
negotiations with Cyprus on January 1, 1995 - but few expect EU leaders to
commit themselves to a firm date.
</TEXT>
